// ANGLAIS
$title_en ='Map types';
$content_en = '<h2>Mapping Europe</h2>';
$content_en .= '<p>Geographic data are the fuel that powers good quality maps. The type and quality of geographic data provide useful alternatives for geographic maps conceptualization and map making. Data are classified by type (quantitative and qualitative data) and locus (geographic location, type of spatial unit of analysis). These data types are used to differentiate geographic information through specific techniques of geographic data representation. Geographic data representation is made through changes in the visual aspect of the various figures used to represent data types. This process calls for the use of what is called “graphic variables” in graphic semiology theory. Other types of data representation can be used to describe a given phenomenon. Geographic richness stems from utilizing various methods among which textual analysis and graphical and cartographic representation either alone or in combination. The representation of maps by categories of variables provides access to various types of geographic subdivisions of Europe (from nuts0 to nuts3 if data required to conduct this kind of geographic subdivision are available) and to other types of representation of a given phenomenon. 7 categories of geographic data representation are proposed: absolute values, ratio values, absolute and ratio values on the same map, discontinuities, cartograms, grids and potentials.</p>';
